    <item>
      <title>Re: Newbie Good Samaritans (AKA Ky's Chatter Box - 11/2/2004)</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&amp;message.id=133289#M133289</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;As a&amp;nbsp;level 5, shaman hunting in qeynos killing snakes, rats and such, this druid (level 40ish)sends me a tell. I didn't even know how to answer a tell, he explained how. He then&amp;nbsp; said, "want me to PL you?". I say "PL?" he agains explains. He then Ports us and takes me to some bandits camps, All the mobs were red and I was scared to death, He buffs me, hit me with DS and points to the first camp "go kill them" .We stayed &amp;nbsp;there&amp;nbsp;until I got to level 9. he then said he had to go, I kept thanking him, I was so amazed a stranger did this. I didn't know about the friends list, but i did write his name on a paper, which i lost a month or so later. I'm now level 70, and often go to the newbie areas and buff the lowbies. If i see a true new player (pretty much naked) I will offer some advice. If they accept and seem nice, I will stay with them and level them a little (not more than 2 level,s they need to work their skills and learn to manage mana and health). I will then give them some plat, decent equiptment or both. I keep them on my friend list a few weeks to make sure they are doing well. I think the best way to stay interested in the game is too help others. it's a real rush to see someone understand something new. To watch them gain confidence and really get into the game. I always ask them to please return the favor to another newbie&amp;nbsp;when they can. I've seen many acts of kindness, starting with that nice druid who took the time to help and explain to a newbie how the game works.&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
